 the law and mobilised police to support the titheowners. Meanwhile, the Church of England and lay titheowners - including Oxford and Cambridge colleges, public schools and major landowners - sought to vindicate their right to tithe; in a particularly shameful episode, the Church established a secret company to buy taken produce and remove it from farms.This "tithe war" was fought outside farms, in the courts, in the press and in the wider arena of public opinion. It posed problems for the Church, legal system, and every political party; split the National Farmers' Union; and provided opportunities for the British Union of Fascists and other sections of the extreme right to cause disturbance.Drawing on extensive archival research, accounts in local newspapers, and private papers, John Bulaitis traces the evolution of what has been described as this "curious rural revolt", from the late nineteenth century to its climax in 1936, when the Tithe Act brought an end to this form of tax.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aTithe War, 1829-1838. 4aModern History. 4aSocial History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  a1930s Rural Revolt.  aAgricultural Depression.  aAgricultural History.  aEcclesiastical Commissioners.  aNational Farmers' Union (NFU).  aQueen Anne's Bounty.  aRural Politics.  aRural Social History.  aTithe Acts.  aTithe Rentcharge.  aTithe War.  aTithepayers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311143096640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805433361?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805433361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805433361/original  a978-3-11-143096-6  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles